The paper deals with transmission schemes and error exponent lower bounds for channels with memory and feedback, which are topics typically studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and signal processing (cs.SI) sub-fields. The use of unifilar channels and the analysis of the log-likelihood ratio suggest a connection to the areas of dynamical systems (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the presence of common randomness and the study of multi-step drift may also relate to the sub-field of network information theory (cs.NI).
